│ "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe repro shows GVN replaces a      │
│ dominated call to llvm.ctpop.i32 (%ctpop2 with !range [0, 33)) with another   │
│ call (%ctpop1 with !range [1, 32)). The replacement causes the target IR to   │
│ use %ctpop1 (with the more restrictive !range metadata) in the if.else block  │
│ where %ctpop2 originally lived. Alive2 reports \"Target is more poisonous     │
│ than source\" because with %x = 0, %ctpop1 actually computes 0, but its       │
│ !range(1,32) metadata makes the SSA value poison as 0 is outside the stated   │
│ range. In the source, %ctpop2 carried a wider range allowing 0 and was        │
│ safe.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- GVN's first transformation is removing    │
│ %ctpop2 and replacing its uses with %ctpop1 via                               │
│ patchAndReplaceAllUsesWith.\n- The AA info shows NoModRef between the ctpop   │
│ calls, so GVN considers them identical and CSEs them.\n- The transformed      │
│ target shows %res = icmp eq i32 %ctpop1, 1 in if.else, and the original       │
│ carried %ctpop2 with a wider !range.\n- The debug shows the transformation    │
│ point in GVN.cpp::patchAndReplaceAllUsesWith and it calls                     │
│ patchReplacementInstruction(I, Repl) first.\n\n3. Root Cause                  │
│ Analysis:\npatchReplacementInstruction (in Transforms/Utils/Local.cpp)        │
│ adjusts IR flags and combines metadata conservatively for alias scopes, but   │
│ it doesn't account for result metadata like !range and !noundef that can      │
│ introduce poison. When reusing Repl's result value in new uses, keeping a     │
│ more restrictive !range than the replaced value (or when the replaced         │
│ instruction has no such metadata) makes the replacement more poisonous than   │
│ the source program, violating correctness.\n\nSpecifically, !range on an      │
│ instruction's result constrains the value and induces poison if the actual    │
│ runtime value falls outside the range. By forwarding %ctpop1 (with !range     │
│ [1,32)) to uses originally of %ctpop2 (with !range [0,33)), GVN ends up       │
│ asserting a stronger range at those use sites. This is invalid unless we can  │
│ prove the stronger range holds along all paths to those uses, which GVN does  │
│ not. Therefore, patchReplacementInstruction must drop or relax                │
│ poison-generating result metadata on the replacement when performing          │
│ cross-use merges.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- File:                      │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/Local.cpp\n- Function:                              │
│ llvm::patchReplacementInstruction(Instruction *I, Value *Repl)\n- Edit        │
│ region: lines 3491-3521\n\nInsert logic to conservatively strip               │
│ poison-generating result metadata from the replacement when its metadata      │
│ could be more restrictive than the original, specifically for !range (and     │
│ potentially other similar metadata). A safe fix is:\n- If ReplInst carries    │
│ MD_range and the instruction being replaced 'I' either does not carry         │
│ MD_range or carries a different MD_range node, drop MD_range from ReplInst    │
│ before combining other metadata.\n- This ensures the replacement isn't more   │
│ poisonous than the source at new use sites.\n\nPseudo-diff within the         │
│ function:\n\nAfter handling IR flags (and before combineMetadataForCSE):\n\n  │
│ // If the replacement has result !range metadata that is stricter than the\n  │
│ // original or the original doesn't have !range, conservatively drop it to\n  │
│ // avoid making the replacement more poisonous at new use sites.\n  if        │
│ (MDNode *ReplRange = ReplInst->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range)) {\n        │
│ MDNode *OrigRange = I->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range);\n    if            │
│ (!OrigRange || OrigRange != ReplRange)\n                                      │
│ ReplInst->setMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range, nullptr);\n  }\n\nWe             │
│ intentionally use pointer equality for comparing MD nodes here as a           │
│ conservative guard: if they differ (including the case where the original     │
│ lacks MD_range), we drop the replacement's range.\n\nNo other behavior change │
│ is needed. combineMetadataForCSE will still conservatively combine            │
│ alias-related metadata as before.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy dropping MD_range     │
│ from the replacement when the original doesn't have the same range metadata,  │
│ we prevent GVN from introducing overly restrictive range assumptions at new   │
│ use sites, avoiding poison mismatches and preserving correctness. This fixes  │
│ the Alive2 counterexample and aligns with the intent that GVN should not make │
│ the transformed program more undefined than the original."})                  │
