│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The repro shows GVN replaces a dominated call to llvm.ctpop.i32 (%ctpop2 with │
│ !range [0, 33)) with another call (%ctpop1 with !range [1, 32)). The          │
│ replacement causes the target IR to use %ctpop1 (with the more restrictive    │
│ !range metadata) in the if.else block where %ctpop2 originally lived. Alive2  │
│ reports "Target is more poisonous than source" because with %x = 0, %ctpop1   │
│ actually computes 0, but its !range(1,32) metadata makes the SSA value poison │
│ as 0 is outside the stated range. In the source, %ctpop2 carried a wider      │
│ range allowing 0 and was safe.                                                │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ - GVN's first transformation is removing %ctpop2 and replacing its uses with  │
│ %ctpop1 via patchAndReplaceAllUsesWith.                                       │
│ - The AA info shows NoModRef between the ctpop calls, so GVN considers them   │
│ identical and CSEs them.                                                      │
│ - The transformed target shows %res = icmp eq i32 %ctpop1, 1 in if.else, and  │
│ the original carried %ctpop2 with a wider !range.                             │
│ - The debug shows the transformation point in                                 │
│ GVN.cpp::patchAndReplaceAllUsesWith and it calls                              │
│ patchReplacementInstruction(I, Repl) first.                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ patchReplacementInstruction (in Transforms/Utils/Local.cpp) adjusts IR flags  │
│ and combines metadata conservatively for alias scopes, but it doesn't account │
│ for result metadata like !range and !noundef that can introduce poison. When  │
│ reusing Repl's result value in new uses, keeping a more restrictive !range    │
│ than the replaced value (or when the replaced instruction has no such         │
│ metadata) makes the replacement more poisonous than the source program,       │
│ violating correctness.                                                        │
│                                                                               │
│ Specifically, !range on an instruction's result constrains the value and      │
│ induces poison if the actual runtime value falls outside the range. By        │
│ forwarding %ctpop1 (with !range [1,32)) to uses originally of %ctpop2 (with   │
│ !range [0,33)), GVN ends up asserting a stronger range at those use sites.    │
│ This is invalid unless we can prove the stronger range holds along all paths  │
│ to those uses, which GVN does not. Therefore, patchReplacementInstruction     │
│ must drop or relax poison-generating result metadata on the replacement when  │
│ performing cross-use merges.                                                  │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/Local.cpp                                   │
│ - Function: llvm::patchReplacementInstruction(Instruction *I, Value *Repl)    │
│ - Edit region: lines 3491-3521                                                │
│                                                                               │
│ Insert logic to conservatively strip poison-generating result metadata from   │
│ the replacement when its metadata could be more restrictive than the          │
│ original, specifically for !range (and potentially other similar metadata). A │
│ safe fix is:                                                                  │
│ - If ReplInst carries MD_range and the instruction being replaced 'I' either  │
│ does not carry MD_range or carries a different MD_range node, drop MD_range   │
│ from ReplInst before combining other metadata.                                │
│ - This ensures the replacement isn't more poisonous than the source at new    │
│ use sites.                                                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ Pseudo-diff within the function:                                              │
│                                                                               │
│ After handling IR flags (and before combineMetadataForCSE):                   │
│                                                                               │
│   // If the replacement has result !range metadata that is stricter than the  │
│   // original or the original doesn't have !range, conservatively drop it to  │
│   // avoid making the replacement more poisonous at new use sites.            │
│   if (MDNode *ReplRange = ReplInst->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range)) {     │
│     MDNode *OrigRange = I->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range);                │
│     if (!OrigRange || OrigRange != ReplRange)                                 │
│       ReplInst->setMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range, nullptr);                  │
│   }                                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ We intentionally use pointer equality for comparing MD nodes here as a        │
│ conservative guard: if they differ (including the case where the original     │
│ lacks MD_range), we drop the replacement's range.                             │
│                                                                               │
│ No other behavior change is needed. combineMetadataForCSE will still          │
│ conservatively combine alias-related metadata as before.                      │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By dropping MD_range from the replacement when the original doesn't have the  │
│ same range metadata, we prevent GVN from introducing overly restrictive range │
│ assumptions at new use sites, avoiding poison mismatches and preserving       │
│ correctness. This fixes the Alive2 counterexample and aligns with the intent  │
│ that GVN should not make the transformed program more undefined than the      │
│ original.                                                                     │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
